president reagan on monday asked congress for a 
small increase in funding for veterans medical care and pensions as 
he proposed outlays of 299 billion for the new department of 
veterans affairs 
outlays for the veterans administration which provided benefits 
and services to veterans for 58 years are estimated to be 292 
billion in fiscal 1989 the budget for the new department which 
assumes cabinet status in march calls for a 700 million increase 
among the budget proposals are a slight increase in outlays for 
medical care including the treatment provided to veterans at 
hospitals nursing homes and on an outpatient basis in fiscal 1989 
outlays totaled 114 billion the 1990 budget calls for 115 
billion 
outlays for construction of state extended care facilities 
increased from 37 million in 1989 to 44 million in 1990 while 
outlays for major project construction was cut from 527 million to 
514 million 
the budget proposes using construction funds for two large 
hospital projects in palm beach fla and newington conn 
proposed outlays for total pensions are 4 billion a 94 million 
increase over the estimated total for fiscal 1989 veterans age 65 
or older with low incomes and wartimeservice are entitled to the 
pensions the wartimeservice does not differentiate between combat 
or noncombat duty 
the pension payments also included a 4 percent costofliving 
increase effective this month 
total outlays for income security for disabled aged or deceased 
veterans in the 1990 budget are 164 billion up from 156 billin 
in 1989 
the reagan administration in the budget also recommends linking 
future veterans compensation costofliving adjustments to annual 
changes in the consumer price index 
the administration also proposes changes in the veterans housing 
program including orgination fees for participating in federal 
credit programs the budget plan did not specify the cost of the 
fees 
two other recommendations affecting housing for veterans propose 
legislation to increase the expiring fee charged on guaranteed 
housing loans and vendee loans and to allow negotiated interest 
rates on guaranteed mortgages 
the expiring fee charge would increase from 1 percent to 38 
percent of the mortgage amount and the borrower could add the fee to 
the mortgage a vendee loan is a direct loan made to veterans and 
nonveterans who purchase property that the veterans administration 
acquired through defaults 
the administration also is seeking budget authority of 15 
million for the court of veterans appeals which would allow 
veterans to appeal some benefit decisions of the departments board 
of veterans appeals 
facing a major cut are grants for the construction of state 
veterans cemeteries which would be reduced from 5 million in 1989 
to 19 million in 1990 
