for construction of a soccer stadium in jerusalem a move opposed by 
ultraorthodox jews who fear weekend games will desecrate the 
sabbath 
the ruling which orders the interior ministry to sign the 
building permit ended a 15year battle to get the athletic field 
built according to the office of jerusalem mayor teddy kollek 
kollek hailed the decision as a victory for jerusalems youth 
who must travel to the coastal city of jaffa to see betar jerusalem 
the team with the largest following 
kollek along with liberal parliament member dedi zucker and a 
group of sports fans filed the petition to the high court a year 
and a half ago 
i share the happiness of the residents and sports fans of the 
capital kollek said in a statement 
he said the stadium would be built as soon as possible 
adding septembers soccer season will open in a new stadium 
construction has been blocked by the interior ministry which 
refused to sign the building permit despite approval for the arena 
from all necessary local government and planning authorities 
the ministry which traditionally is headed by an orthodox 
minister argued that noise from the stadium and its parking lot 
could disrupt religious jews on the sabbath which begins at sundown 
friday and continues until sundown saturday 
the religious also argued that building the stadium would 
encourage jews to break the sabbath by driving to see games 
most soccer games in israel are played on saturday 
interior ministry spokeswoman tova elinson said there would be no 
comment on the ruling until the minister arye deri returned from 
the united states on tuesday 
the 12000seat stadium is to be built in the malha neighborhood 
in southwestern jerusalem many residents of the bayit vagan 
neighborhood to the north are orthodox jews 
the site has a grass playing field but no seating and no parking 
facilities construction is expected to cost about 24 million 
zucker a member of the leftleaning citizens rights party 
described the ruling as a victory for secular jews he noted 18 
months ago we opened the town for theaters and movies on fridays 
and now we have given the town what it is entitled to have like any 
other city in israel a stadium 
