<DOCNO> AP890109-0173 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
compass needles dont always point north a 
problem that may be eased by a new series of charts prepared by the 
federal government 
compasses are oriented by the earths magnetic field and since 
that is shifting over time the direction the needle points changes 
also 
this may mean little to most people but it can be a serious 
problem for engineers navigators mapmakers hikers scientists and 
others who need to know where they are going 
a person following the compass needle in the florida panhandle 
for example would be walking due north 
but someone following his compass in maine would be going 21 
degrees to the west while an alaskan would be heading 35 degrees 
east of north 
the us geological survey has compiled a series of 10 new 
magnetic charts five for the united states and five for the globe 
showing variances in different areas 
because of the time needed to compile these complex maps the 
charts are current for 1985 and contain correction estimates for the 
next few years so users can keep current with the changing magnetic 
field 
the united states charts cost 620 each and those for the globe 
are 310 apiece ordering information can be obtained from the us 
geological survey map distribution branch box 25286 federal 
center denver colo 80225 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

