<DOCNO> AP890109-0185 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the recent discovery of a black widow binary a 
star that destroys its orbiting companion like the spider that eats 
its mate may provide a missing link in the evolution of the 
heavens astronomers said monday 
the object is a rapidly spinning binary pulsar a dead collapsed 
star that is orbited by a larger ordinary star 
astronomers have discovered that the pulsar is blasting away its 
companion in the last phase of an intricate give and take between 
the two distant orbs 
the companion is being destroyed said frederic a rasio of 
cornell university it is constantly losing matter eventually it 
could completely disappear 
astronomers say it appears that the pulsar uses its companion to 
build up tremendous spinning speed then turns on its mate burning 
it up 
the pulsar is one of a small group of such objects that spin 
extremely rapidly the newly discovered pair is important because it 
seems to help explain how they get to spin so fast 
it offers a missing link between two classes of objects said 
steve maran of the goddard space flight center thats why 
astronomers are so excited 
the pulsar and its mate were discovered last spring by andrew 
fruchter of the carnegie institution in washington its implications 
were described monday at a meeting here of the american astronomical 
society 
a pulsar is an extremely dense collapsed star made up of 
neutrons it is the remains of a large star that was destroyed in a 
spectacular explosion called a supernova 
pulsars give off no light but they broadcast twin rotating beams 
of radar like lighthouses in the sky 
a pulsar is minute compared to the sun but its mass is 50 
percent greater one teaspoon of pulsar matter weighs billions of 
tons 
most pulsars spin about once a second and are slowing down 
however the newly discovered one known as psr 195720 is one of 
six discovered so far in the milky way that spin much faster in 
this case about 600 times a second 
astronomers theorize that these pulsars speed up by stealing a 
stream of matter from a companion star the companion spins up the 
pulsar like a top said fruchter 
however while some of these fastspinning pulsars have 
companions others do not 
people wondered if you spin up the pulsar with a companion 
where is the companion said fruchter this may explain that 
the pulsar has evaporated the companion 
in the newly spotted couple the companion is very near the 
pulsar just the distance of two and a half times the diameter of 
the sun yet it is being bombarded with a blaze of atomic particles 
5000 times more intense than the sun 
this is the only one mateeating one that we have seen in the 
galaxy but there is the exciting possibility that there will be 
many more said e sterl phinney of california institute of 
technology 
astronomers were able to study the pair because the companion 
regularly eclipses the pulsar the companion revolves around the 
pulsar once every nine hours and each time it blocks out the 
pulsars radar beam for about 50 minutes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

