tens of thousands of workers in eastern 
hungary staged a 10minute warning strike monday against big price 
increases and trade unions charged the government is picking the 
pockets of the people 
the state news agency mti reported workers in szabolcsszatmar 
county started work with a 10minute delay and said local trade 
union leaders supported their action 
mti estimated the increases that took effect monday will cost 
consumers 15 a month and predicted food consumption will drop 10 
percent to 15 percent in the first half of the year 
behind these stark sets of figures there are human lives 
nepszava the official trade union daily said in a monday editorial 
trade union leaders already have warned the increases could spark 
strikes 
according to the nepszava 10 percent of families in hungary live 
on a smaller monthly income than the official subsistence level of 
72 
inflation amounted to 17 percent in 1988 when real wages dropped 
by 8 percent according to official statistics 
the characteristic feature of the governments financial policy 
will be picking the pockets of the companies and the population 
nepszava charged 
hungarian officials monday told journalists the price rises were 
needed to reduce state subsidies and balance the budget they are 
part of a series of economic reforms and austerity measures the 
government is introducing to help reduce hungarys 17 billion 
foreign debt and stimulate the stagnating economy 
trade union leaders support the idea of allowing the market to 
regulate prices but admonished the government to apply these rules 
also to wages 
on what ground does the government believe that labor can be 
bought for less than it costs the paper asked no order no 
stabilization can possibly emerge until honest work is paid by 
honest wages 
other increases planned this year include raising public 
transportation costs by 62 percent feb 1 and household water and 
sewage fees by 220 percent to 290 percent march 1 
in budapest and elsewhere citizens anticipated the price hikes 
by stockpiling leaving food shop shelves completely bare last week 
prices of pork poultry and meat preparations went up by 13 
percent to 14 percent from monday andd beef prices increased 30 
percent now consumers pay 165 for a pound of medium quality beef 
and 12 cents for a pint of milk that cost 9 cents last week 
