<TEXT>
women who drink caffeinated 
beverages may take longer to become pregnant say scientists at the 
national institute of environmental health sciences 
every epidemiologic study has limitations said dr allen j 
wilcox principal investigator the findings were strong among 
women in our study but we wont be convinced until other 
epidemiologists find the same results in other groups 
the study was published in december in the lancet a british 
medical journal 
the study of caffeines effects on pregnancy was made as part of 
a study of early pregnancy in which women planning to become 
pregnant were enrolled at the time they stopped using birth control 
a group of 104 women provided data on the amount of caffeinated 
beverages they consumed during the time they tried to conceive the 
study said women who drank more than one cup of caffeinated coffee 
a day or the equivalent in tea and colas took significantly longer 
to become pregnant than women who drank less 
the husbands caffeine consumption has no apparent effect the 
study said factors such as smoking alcohol consumption frequency 
of intercourse and womens age did not change the findings 
even if the effect is real there is no evidence that caffeine 
does permanent harm wilcox said our data suggests that it is 
the womens current caffeine consumption not her past habits that 
affects her fertility 
fortunately women can avoid caffeinated beverages if 
necessary also there were women in our study who became pregnant 
quickly even while drinking large amounts of coffee obviously if 
caffeine is an influence on fertility it is not the only influence 
some women may be more susceptible to caffeine effects than others 
</TEXT>
