<TEXT>
the reagan administration on monday proposed to 
boost spending for aids research and prevention by 13 percent but to 
reduce the growth of the medicare and medicaid health programs by 
cutting payments to states hospitals and physicians 
overall the budget of the department of health and human 
services the largest federal department would increase 57 
percent to 4244 billion in fiscal 1990 hhs spending accounts for 
about 37 percent of the federal budget 
medicare and medicaid have been fueling the growth of the 
departments budget medicare has been growing faster than the 
number of beneficiaries and far more rapidly than inflation even 
inflation in medical prices between 1980 and 1989 medicare has 
grown about 12 percent annually while medicaid is growing at 13 
percent a year 
president reagan said his proposed cutbacks would not reduce 
benefits to the 56 million elderly disabled and lowincome people 
in the two programs but would force the states which administer 
medicaid and providers paid by medicare to become more efficient 
and reduce waste 
reagans critics however say the medicaid cutbacks which will 
reduce grants to states by 3 percent will curtail medical services 
for the poor 
unless states have or are willing to come up with more money 
which many arent their only options are to restrict eligibility 
reduce medical services or reduce fees paid to doctors said 
robert greenstein director of the center on budget and policy 
priorities a nonprofit group that researches policy issues 
affecting the lowincome 
in substantial part it will be passed along in benefit 
reductions he said 
rep henry waxman dcalif chairman of the house health 
subcommittee said the medicaid cutbacks put the states in a 
financially untenable situation that will result in less coverage 
to lowincome families 
reagan said the fight against the spread of acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome continues to be the nations top public health 
priority an estimated 1 million to 15 million people in the united 
states are infected with the deadly virus though not all have 
developed symptoms yet 
reagan proposed 160 million more for aids research which would 
bring spending in fiscal 1990 to 14 billion a 13 percent increase 
over current outlays 
hhs secretary otis bowen had pushed for a 39 percent increase 
over the 1989 budget authority of 13 billion but the proposed 
spending plan would increase spending authority by only 24 percent 
to 16 billion for fiscal 1990 budget authority totals can be 
spent over more than one year 
the department also estimated an additional 925 million would be 
spent on treatment and income support to aids victims through 
medicaid medicare disability insurance and other income and 
service programs 
more than 82000 aids cases have been reported in the united 
states since 1981 by the end of 1992 the administration said 
reported aids cases in this country are expected to reach 365000 
with 80000 new cases and 65000 aids deaths projected for that year 
alone 
the budget proposal also increases basic biomedical research by 
66 percent to 85 million included is 100 million for a project 
to map the human genome the biological blueprint that determines 
individual characteristics and that also can cause disease 
more than 94 percent of hhs spending is earmarked for entitlement 
programs like social security medicare and medicaid over which the 
agency has little budget control since eligibility for the programs 
is set by congress 
reagans budget protects social security benefits but proposes 
changes that would require approval by congress to reduce the rapid 
growth in medicare and medicaid spending 
hospitals have a lot of profit margin with which to absorb 
the reductions and states need to examine how they are running 
their medicaid programs not necessarily cut back benefits said 
elizabeth cusick director of the division of health benefits in the 
office of the hhs secretary 
we want to encourage them to find ways to control costs she 
said 
without any changes the medicare budget which pays for the 
health care of about 34 million elderly and disabled americans 
would grow by 14 percent in fiscal 1990 however reagan is 
proposing to trim that growth rate to 10 percent by cutting 35 
billion from fees paid to physicians and hospitals the medicare 
budget would total 949 billion 
about a third of the medicare cut 1 billion would come from 
cuts in payments to teaching hospitals which receive additional 
reimbursements to cover their costs of training interns and 
residents 
also capital payments to hospitals would be cut for a savings of 
620 million and reduced fees to physicians for certain procedures 
including radiology anesthesiology and surgery that are considered 
overpriced would save about 350 million 
a new part of medicare is the catastrophic health insurance 
program which is intended to be entirely selfsupporting it is 
financed by premiums paid by medicare recipients which are 
projected to total about 86 billion in fiscal 1990 the program is 
projected to spend 4 billion in that year 
growth in medicaid the program that rovides health care for 
about 26 million lowincome americans would be 9 percent without 
changes in the program next year the administration is proposing to 
slice that to 5 percent growth with cuts totalling about 14 
billion for a spending a total of 36 billion 
much of the reduction would come from reducing payments to the 
states which administer the program under federal guidelines by 
about 11 billion 
benefits under the social security program are protected and the 
administration projects a costofliving adjustment of 36 percent 
in january 1990 
currently a newly retired 65yearold can receive a maximum of 
899 per month in social security benefits a 36 percent increase 
would put the maximum at 931 next year 
