<TEXT>
this island of 12000 people has been 
british since 1783 but a carved wooden shamrock perches on the 
colonial governors roof and an immigration officer will stamp the 
irish symbol in your passport 
montserrat a pearshaped haven of densely forested mountains 
palm trees multicolored flowers and grayblack volcanic beaches 
between antigua and guadeloupe is a hint of ireland in the 
caribbean 
tourist brochures call it the emerald isle st patricks day is 
a legal holiday and a version of irish stew is a local delicacy 
although the population is 98 percent black and the climate 
semitropical you can flip through the telephone book and imagine 
yourself in killarney row after row of ryans rileys and ogarros 
both the head of government and his main rival are named osborne 
chief minister john and opposition leader bertrand a distant cousin 
driving around montserrat a hilly 11 miles long and seven wide 
you pass st patricks cork hill sweeneys estate carrs bay 
bransby point and galways soufriere a volcanic crater of bubbling 
sulfur 
in the north you find the most irish montserratians of all the 
socalled black irish who make up 10 percent of the population and 
are as likely as not to speak with a hint of brogue and have a tinge 
of red in the hair 
most other montserratians are descendants of slaves who took 
their masters names after emancipation in 1832 when irish people 
greatly outnumbered english on the island 
anthropologist john messenger of ohio state university said the 
black irish descend directly from legal marriages in the 17th 
century between african slaves and irish plantation owners and 
irish customs were passed down through the centuries 
they are very closeknit and inbred he said and three 
family names predominate gibbons sweeney and allen 
among them messenger found montserrats last known irish fiddler 
a few years ago he held the fiddle in the crook of his arm and 
his daughter did an irish stepdance the anthropologist said 
messenger and his wife betty a fellow anthropologist at ohio 
state have been digging at montserrats irish roots since 1965 
they were making their 20th or so visit over the christmasnew year 
school break and talked about their work 
christopher columbus sighted the island in 1493 and named it for 
the serrated mountains and abbey of montserrat in spain the english 
settled montserrat in the early 1600s and gained undisputed control 
in 1783 after a series of wars with the french 
john messenger said there is historical evidence the irish 
arrived in two separate groups in the same year 1632 and settled 
on different parts of the island one contingent came from nearby 
st kitts and the other from jamestown in virginia colony both to 
escape protestant persecution he said 
before long the irish outnumbered the english on montserrat 
they established many of the sugar lime and tobacco plantations 
worked by imported slaves a census record in 1678 gave the 
population as 52 scots 761 english 992 slaves and 1869 irish 
irish people settled throughout the caribbean but became 
concentrated here 
messenger said there was little awareness of the the islands 
irish past until he and his wife wrote several articles for the 
irish times of dublin in 1967 and lectured in ireland 
since then two films on the black irish have been shown in 
europe and the irish and irishamericans have become interested 
we got the ball rolling the anthropologist said 
he said the montserrat tourist industry has promoted the irish 
connection in hopes of attracting irishamericans an estimated 
1500 to 2000 of whom visited last year 
most islanders dont seem all that interested however howard 
fergus a faculty member at the university of the west indies and 
montserrats leading historian suggested irishness is not something 
they would to boast about 
i dont think there is any attachment to the irish he said 
people celebrate st patricks day here but apart from the church 
connection a number of us celebrate it because on that day there was 
a slave rebellion on march 17 1768 
about his own name being irish fergus said yes but it 
doesnt mean anything to me it merely is a slave name the 
irish are white people 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890109-0283 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
perhaps the best thing that ever happened to 20000 
americans with the bleeding disease hemophilia was the discovery of 
treatment with a protein called factor viii it was also probably 
the worst 
fiveminute infusions of this natural substance overcome their 
bodies inability to form blood clots so they can lead nearly normal 
lives but the price has been disastrously high the treatments also 
have given more than half of them aids infections 
the treatment has been made safe again but another crisis looms 
factor viii is in severe sometimes lifethreateningly short supply 
in the new york region weve used 30 to 40 percent less 
clotting factor in 1988 said dr richard lipton of long island 
jewish medical center i dont know if i can say anyone has died 
because of this but we have had some pretty hairy situations trying 
to find factor viii for people who are bleeding 
doctors say that because of the shortage most nonemergency 
surgery has been postponed for hemophiliacs bleeding often is 
treated with less than the recommended doses sometimes with poor 
results users have smaller reserves for emergencies most have 
stopped taking preventive doses and now use clotting factor only for 
actual bleeding 
they also have had to rely more on cryoprecipitate an older 
less convenient therapy that requires a trip to the hospital to 
receive blood plasma that is rich in factor viii this treatment 
carries the same very slight risk of aids as an ordinary blood 
transfusion 
the shortage has produced a tremendous amount of frustration 
and in some people despair in some anger and in some resignation 
said donald s goldman a lawyer from west orange nj who has 
hemophilia 
hemophiliacs represent just 1 percent of the 80000 aids cases 
reported in the united states since 1982 however a larger 
proportion of them are infected than are the other two major risk 
groups homosexual men and drug addicts 
about 60 percent of us hemophiliacs are infected and for those 
with the most severe form of the disease its perhaps 80 percent to 
90 percent said alan brownstein executive director of the national 
hemophilia foundation 
while most of the hemophiliacs who carry the aids virus are still 
healthy doctors fear that many of them will eventually get aids 
hemophilia is caused by a genetic defect passed from mothers to 
sons at conception victims dont produce enough factor viii one 
link in the chemical chain reaction that prompts the body to stop 
bleeding without treatment cuts may bleed for days but the most 
common problem is bleeding internally bleeding into the joints 
causes crippling deformities 
once the only treatment for hemophilia was blood transfusions 
then blood plasma was substituted in the 1960s cryoprecipitate 
became the standard finally in the 1970s factor viii became 
available instead of 30 to 50 trips a year to a hospital for 
infusions people with severe cases could quickly treat themselves 
at work or at home 
we are talking about people who aside from the horrible aids 
tragedy have been liberated by clotting factor said brownstein 
a person with hemophilia can do any job now if they have a 
spontaneous bleeding episode they can mix their preparations and 
infuse themselves on the spot they can do it as conveniently in a 
747 as in their own living room 
factor viii is derived from human blood it takes about 30 liters 
to produce enough clotting factor for one treatment in commercial 
production blood plasma from many people is mixed together a 
single dose may contain elements of blood from 20000 people or more 
no one knew it at the time but during late 1970s and early 
1980s aids virus in the donated blood passed through the 
purification process into the factor viii in 1982 the us centers 
for disease control reported the first three suspected cases of aids 
among hemophiliacs 
in 1984 manufacturers began heating the clotting factor in an 
effort to kill hiv the aids virus and a year later a test became 
available to screen donated blood for the virus since then factor 
viii makers have adopted other cleansing techniques including 
detergents and antibodies 
since 1985 only 18 new aids infections have been documented 
said brownstein who believes the latest strategies have made 
clotting factor hivfree but they have also made it expensive and 
scarce the new processes yield only about half as much factor viii 
per liter as the earlier techniques 
robert w reilly president of the american blood resources 
association an industry group said the price has risen six to 
sevenfold since 1985 enough clotting factor for one person now 
typically costs about 50000 a year brownstein said 
the price and supply were also affected by low demand for 
albumin until recently factor viii was simply a byproduct of the 
business of producing albumin which was used to restore blood 
volume after surgery and burns however albumin is being replaced 
by newer treatments 
factor vii was already in short supply at the start of 1988 but 
the situation became much worse because of problems at the american 
red cross which produces about 20 percent of the countrys clotting 
factor 
last april the red cross discovered it had allowed factor viii 
to be made from blood that should have been discarded because of 
potential aids contamination dr s gerald sandler vice president 
for blood services said that most of this was from people whose 
blood twice tested positive for hiv during initial screening but was 
shown by later confirmatory tests to be safe 
these donations were thrown out but the donors were later 
allowed to give blood again this time their blood passed the 
initial screening test however because of their earlier positive 
results acceptance of the blood was a violation of food and drug 
administration rules 
since then the red cross has released little factor viii 
although it recently resumed production meanwhile about 7 percent 
of the nations usual annual production is on hold officials of the 
red cross and fda believe it is safe but because of errors in the 
way it was produced fda officials say they would be breaking their 
rules if they allowed its release 
paul parkman director of the fdas center for biologics 
evaluation and research said the fda might allow the questionable 
factor to be released as an experimental drug users would have to 
sign consent statements acknowledging that they understood the 
protein did not meet federal standards 
brownstein said that last year 675 million units of factor viii 
were available in the united states and 591 million were used in 
1988 about 450 million units were available and virtually all of 
it was used 
reilly said the major commercial makers expect to improve 
production during 1989 and with the red cross back in business the 
shortage should begin to ease during the second half of 1989 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

