theres a new twist in the tax law for sports 
fans who give to the ol alma mater 
even if your gift to a college or university entitles you to buy 
season tickets you still may take a charitable deduction for 80 
percent of your donation 
this new law enacted last year overturns a 1983 ruling by the 
internal revenue service 
the irs noted that in many cases games are sold out long in 
advance and the only way to be assured of getting a ticket is to 
make a donation to the college or its athletic programs therefore 
the irs insisted the privilege of buying a ticket had value and a 
charitable deduction is prohibited when the donor receives something 
of value in return 
lawmakers would have none of that so under a 1988 law you may 
deduct 80 percent of such contributions if as part of the 
arrangemnt you receive the right to purchase tickets if you 
receive no such right the contribution is 100 percent deductible 
if you receive tickets as part of the deal none of the contribution 
may be deducted 
the new law applies retroactively to contributions given after 
dec 31 1983 
