<TEXT>
capital gains are an aspect of tax law that 
most people encounter only in connection with the sale of their 
home but in many cases taxation on profits from a home sale is 
deferred or avoided entirely 
in general the law treats such gains in much the same way that 
it treats profits from the sale of stock land coins or other 
property that means any profit is taxable income and under the new 
law there is no automatic exclusion of a portion of capital gains 
however there are two outs when the capital gain is from the 
sale of your principal home 
first if certain conditions are met any tax on the gain is 
deferred so long as you buy a replacement home that costs at least 
as much as your old home sold for the replacement must be bought 
within 24 months before or 24 months after the old one is sold 
if your new one costs less than the adjusted selling price of 
your old home you pay tax on the profit from the sale or on the 
portion of the sales price that exceeds the cost of the new home 
whichever is less you reduce the tax bite by adjusting the sales 
price of the old home to reflect points fixup expenses real 
estate commissions and legal fees you paid 
deferral of gain on your home sale is not optional you must do 
it anytime you buy a principal home whose price equals or exceeds 
the adjusted sales price of your old one 
second if you or your spouse are 55 or older you may avoid 
tax on the first 125000 of profits this option is available only 
once in a lifetime to qualify the property must have been your 
principal home for at least three of the last five years before the 
sale 
the miscellaneous tax bill that congress passed last october made 
two minor changes affecting these provisions 
one ensures that a couple will not be denied the benefits of the 
deferral because one spouse dies after the old home is sold but 
before the new one is bought 
the second stipulates that a person 55 or older who becomes 
mentally or physically incapable of selfcare during the fiveyear 
period preceding the home sale will be deemed to have met the 
residency requirement if up to four of the five years are spent in a 
nursing home 
if you sold a principal home in 1988 you should check 
publication 523 which is free from the irs whether you purchased a 
replacement home or claimed the special benefit for those 55 or 
older you probably will have to file a form 2119 
any gain that is taxable must be reported on 1040 schedule d 
did you sell your home in 1988 and wont receive some of the 
proceeds until 1989 or later you may have to report such 
installment sales on form 6252 
</TEXT>
