<DOCNO> AP890109-0330 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday said it will use a 
dispute over royalties from aerosol valves to answer a question 
involving the authority of federal appeals courts 
the court agreed to hear an appeal by an illinois corporation 
that sued four venezuelans and a us citizen living in venezuela 
the company newmangreen inc has been making aerosol valves 
for more than 30 years it arranged in the early 1970s to market the 
valves in venezuela and set up a licensing agreement with five 
shareholders of the venture in the south american country 
newmangreen filed a suit in federal court in illinois in 1982 
accusing the five of violating the royalty agreement 
the five include william l bettison a us citizen who lives in 
venezuela 
a federal judge awarded newmangreen 200000 in unpaid royalties 
but said the venezuelan shareholders did not owe royalties for a 
period after the us company canceled its license with the 
venezuelan shareholders 
newmangreen asked a threejudge panel of the 7th us circuit 
court of appeals for increased royalties 
the panel then noticed that the federal courts appeared to lack 
authority over the dispute because of the presence of bettison as a 
defendant 
federal courts have jurisdiction in such disputes when the 
opposing sides are from different states or from different nations 
bettisons lack of residency in the united states while still a 
us citizen jeopardized federal court jurisdiction the panel said 
but the panel said the problem was solved by eliminating bettison 
as a defendant it then ruled that newmangreen is entitled to 
additional royalties from the other four 
that decision was overturned last august by the full 7th circuit 
court in an 83 ruling 
the full appeals court said the threejudge panel lacked the 
authority to dismiss bettison from the case and sent the dispute 
back to the federal judge who presided originally over the suit 
the appeals court said the judge must decide the next step which 
could be to dismiss bettison as a defendant 
we can find no source for a power in a court of appeals to 
preserve jurisdiction by dismissing a party retroactively to 
the date the suit was filed the full 7th circuit court said 
newmangreen appealed to the supreme court to reinstate the 
ruling by the threejudge panel 
the case is newmangreen vs alfonzolarrain 88774 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

