<TEXT>
the reagan administration on monday dumped the 
savings and loan crisis into the lap of presidentelect bush 
acknowledging for the first time it does not have enough money to 
bail out the troubled industry 
the administration in its proposed budget for fiscal year 1990 
outlined plans to spend 64 billion from the federal savings and 
loan insurance corp from 1989 through 1994 of that 16 billion 
would be spent in fiscal 1989 which began last oct 1 9 billion 
in 1990 and 39 billion from 1991 through 1994 
but the budget document acknowledged these proposals will not 
resolve the entire problem it said treasury secretary nicholas f 
brady is working on a plan including identifying additional 
funding sources for fslic to be presented to bush within 60 days 
the budget shows spending of 64 billion over six years but 
projects collections by the fslic of only 334 billion that does 
not necessarily mean however the 306 billion difference will 
have to be made up with tax dollars immediately 
the insurance fund which guarantees deposit accounts up to 
100000 can continue as it has over the past year to spend in 
the form of promissory notes to bailedout institutions 
the notes count as immediate spending for budget purposes but 
until they come due sometimes 10 years later the agency spends only 
enough cash to cover the interest 
another kind of commitment from sampl regulators promises to make 
good on some of the future losses of rescued institutions do not 
show up on the budget at all until the cash is actually spent 
in calendar year 1988 sampl regulators spent or promised to 
spend more than 38 billion to rescue a postdepression record 217 
insolvent savings and loans however that still leaves a large 
problem about 350 insolvent institutions and another 150 with 
capital levels close to insolvency 
the reagan budget document maintains that of the 25 billion in 
projected spending for 1989 and 1990 10 billion in 1989 and 5 
billion in 1990 will be for new case resolutions and the rest to 
pay for old rescue deals 
however reagan budget director joseph r wright jr 
acknowledged most of the 10 billion for new deals in 1989 was 
alreadly spent in the first three months of the fiscal year 
our point is this should allow the fslic to handle the most 
troubled institutions its not like this is the final 
solution wright said any additional money should be linked to 
reforms of the regulatory system he said 
if you just pour money into it and leave the industry operating 
the way it is now you can find yourself pouring it in again in 
eight to 10 years he warned 
an official of the general accounting office the auditing wing 
of congress said regulators appear to have already committed 
themselves to spending all of their projected revenue for the next 
decade 
based on what ive seen i think theyve spent it all or maybe 
even more than they can count on receiving over the next 10 years 
said craig simmons a ga analyst 
according to the federal home loan bank board the fslics parent 
agency the insurance fund will collect about 22 billion a year in 
assessments from member sampls 
under legislation passed by congress in 1987 it has authority to 
sell bonds to raise another 55 billion this year and next plus 
over the next five years it expects to realize 9 billion from the 
sale of property previously owned by insolvent sampls 
the gao is analyzing the fslics finances to determine whether it 
faces a cash crunch in the future by the end of 1990 the bank 
board will have issued 106 billion in bonds and to date it has 
issued about 25 billion in promissory notes the interest on those 
obligations will run at least 3 billion a year 
bert ely a financial analyst in alexandria va said i think 
theyre facing a cash crunch this year 
the treasury department according to administration sources who 
declined to be identified is studying a number of options f money into 
the insurance fund 
one plan would raise the money through additional borrowing 
taxpayers would pay the interest but the money would be borrowed 
offbudget and would not add to the federal budget deficit an 
independent board incor 
pumping moreluding the treasury secretary would oversee 
regulators spending of the new money 
the reagan budget document while withholding details of the 
treasury plan outlined its principles 
insured depositors will be protected 
private resources including additional money from the sampl 
industry should be fully explored before any public assistance is 
considered 
reform of the existing regulatory structure should be linked to 
any additional money 
there must be full accountability to the president and the 
congress for any use of additional money 
reforms should aim at maintaining market forces and 
discipline the document did not explain precisely what was meant 
by that phra 
reagan called too for eliminating subsidies that help run 
subways and bus services and terminating a program that keeps air 
service for many small communities 
doctors would have to accept smaller fees for treating the 
elderly under medicare and the poor under medicaid radiologists 
anesthesiologists and surgeons especially would get less 
the nations six million boat owners weekend sailors and 
commercial fishermen alike would have to buy a 25 coast guard 
decal to help defray the costs of rescues in emergencies 
homebuyers would see a nearly fourfold increase in the 1 percent 
fee for va loan guarantees it would rise to 38 percent under 
reagans proposals 
he proposed eliminating the 1990 costofliving increase in 
pensions received by federal retirees and reworking the formula 
under which cola increases are granted so that the retired workers 
would have to absorb the first 1 percent increase in the annual cost 
of living 
workers who lose their jobs to foreign competition now get weekly 
benefits while they look for other work reagan proposed eliminating 
a program which he said works to benefit one group of 
underemployed workers or uncompetitive firms 
